<number box="[1215,1243,1806,1830]" pageId="6" pageNumber="597" value="54.0">54</number>
perigenital setae surrounding GO. Two pairs of distinct outlying setae beside GO. Subgenital setae on genital sclerites, grouped 
<number box="[1393,1410,1842,1866]" pageId="6" pageNumber="597" value="2.0">2</number>
: 
<number box="[1414,1431,1842,1866]" pageId="6" pageNumber="597" value="2.0">2</number>
. Spermatophorotype extending 
<number box="[496,524,1878,1902]" pageId="6" pageNumber="597" value="18.0">18</number>
μm beyond GO (
<figureCitation box="[720,786,1878,1902]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1942,1965]" captionTargetBox="[208,1379,193,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[208,1379,193,1921]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 3. Halacarus todaroi sp. nov., Female: A. Idiosoma, dorsal view. B. Idiosoma, ventral view. C. Gnathosoma, ventral view. D. GA. G, H and I. Legs II, III and IV, respectively; J. Tarsus I; Male, E. GA; F. Leg I. K. Tarsus IV. Scale bars: A, B: 100 μm. C, D and E: 30 μm. F – H and I: 50 μm. J and K: 10 μm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/217873/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="597">
Fig. 
<number box="[772,786,1878,1902]" pageId="6" pageNumber="597" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
E).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="597" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,798,1974]" pageId="6" pageNumber="597">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1915,1939]" pageId="6" pageNumber="597">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name is dedicated to Dr. Antonio Todaro, who gave one of the individuals to the first author, and for his relevant contributions to the knowledge of meiofauna.
</paragraph>
